I prefer to think of them as exciting new challenges rather than dubious
and unproved merits. :) But of course I understand your concerns. I've
been one of the strongest resisters of the encroachment of automation,
and for precisely these reasons. I was on Nomic World, too, and I
learned the same lessons you did. But there are reasons for optimism as
well as skepticism: Shattered World uses the same driver now as Nomic
World did 6 years ago - but that same driver has been subject to 6 years
of improvement. Geoff's view is that it's much more robust and stable
now than Nomic World ever was back then. Its facilities for object
creation by non-wizards have been greatly improved. Geoff thinks that
reifying VTs, for example, would be a "trivial" task.

>Steve> Of course, the requirement that all the administrative business
>Steve> of the game be conducted by email does seriously limit the ways
>Steve> in which we can integrate ourselves into any MUD. 
>
>I don't understand why this is the case.

To me the most exciting opportunities afforded by the move to a MUD are
those that come from the chance to interact with an economy and
political system external to our own, namely, that already in place in
SW. So, I'd like see VTs traded for Coins, which can be used to buy
food. In Shattered World, you have to eat, after all. But I doubt SW
citizens are going to want to trade in VTs they can't see when they
type 'inventory'.

>Steve> For example, we could not allow Voting Tokens to be reified in
>Steve> the game while preserving this requirement. 
>
>I think doing so is a stupendously bad idea; see above.

There are risks, I agree. There are also potential benefits. I'd prefer
to try it and see rather than rule it out in advance without having
tried it. Whatever happened would be interesting, and wasn't that the
whole point?


