Re: DIS: An intriguing proposal 

Steve wrote:

>>I don't think we should shift from email-based play.  For a variety of
>>reasons, I think that the legislative and administrative business of
>>Agora should continue to be conducted in email.

>A number of people have expressed this desire, which is perfectly
>understandable. If it were possible to link notice boards in SW to the
>mailing lists, so that everything that appeared on the notice boards
>would also appeal on the mailing lists, would some of your concerns be
>met?

>Of course, the requirement that all the administrative business of the
>game be conducted by email does seriously limit the ways in which we can
>integrate ourselves into any MUD. For example, we could not allow Voting
>Tokens to be reified in the game while preserving this requirement. At
>some point you have to decide whether a transfer of VTs is achieved by
>sending an email message, or performing an action in the MUD. You can
>have one or the other, but not both. 

>There would remain areas for exploration though. SW already has its own
>Coin economy, and this could interact with ours. The SW program would
>keep track of Coins, while we would use our Recordkeeping system to keep
>track of VTs.

>Still, insisting on retaining the email-based nature of the game does
>lessen the excitement of the proposal, at least for me. The more radical
>idea of trying to convert Agora into a wholly MUD-based Nomic seems more
>challenging, and to hold out more potential for future interest.

>Perhaps we don't have to choose. If enough other Players were interested
>in forming a colonizing party to settle the SW city of Merenth as I've
>suggested, we could simply start the process on our own, and take our
>own copy of the Ruleset with us, effectively forking the game state.
>We wouldn't even have to quit playing Agora to do it.

This last suggestion sounds like the easiest to implement, however it runs the
risk of forcing those of us with less time on our hands to choose one Agora or
the other, thereby diluting both.  Maybe it would be work for both e-mailers
and MUDers to let the development of an economy be wholly MUD-based and let the
manipulation of Rules continue to be e-mail based.  Of course, this would mean
going back to free voting and proposal making.

-- Crito


