A bunch of us were given a guided tour around Shattered World yesterday.
They seemed (at least, the few citizens we spoke with) to be quite
amenable to us moving in to a "city" within their world, and declaring
it to be our domain. The laws they have there are pretty much restricted
to "Sanom City" - the main city in the MUD, but the world is quite big
and there are other cities around which we could move in to.

Which raises the question: if we do "take over" a city in this way, how
do we assert our authority? Working on the definition that government is
"legitimate enforcement", we need to ask "How do we gain legitimacy?" 
and "How do we practice enforcement?".

Legitimacy should be relatively easy. First of all, we should be able 
to get the Gods' approval of what we do, which is pretty much all the
approval we need. It is hard to argue with the Gods. To bolster this,
we ought also to seek Sanom City's official recognition as a separate
state.

Enforcement is a bit harder. I've been trying to find out how Sanom 
handle it. Power seems to come in two forms - money and "physical"
strength. It would appear that the Sanom City council rely on the
former, and use the latter more indirectly. A significant part of their
justice system is the "bounty" arrangement, whereby large sums of 
money are paid for the corpse of some outlawed player. This is probably
fairly effective (depending on how extreme "death" is in the game),
but relies on the government having the funds to pay the bounties, which
can be quite large.

Delgath (our guide) was rather unclear on where the money for bounties
comes from. Apparently there is some "City Treasury" which funds them,
and which is in turn funded by sales of real-estate in the city, and
similar things. We would have to see whether a similar account could
be set up for us in our city, and how we could fill it.

I would like to talk with the Wizards and Gods of the world before we
do anything, but I for one am quite intrigued by the possibilities that
moving into SW would open to us - a real "populace", a complex economic
system, and close contact with a foreign government. It could be lots
of fun.

